This Mithridates is stated by Dio to have been a descendant of the great Mithridates, and to have received his kingdom from Claudius (41 A. D.) in succession to Polemo, who was transferred to Cilicia. Subsequently Claudius deposed him, and set up his brother Cotys in his stead (46 A. D.) ; cf. ch. 18, 1.

This kingdom, having Panticapaeum for its capital, and extending over most of the Crimea, with an undefined supremacy over the tribes east of the Cimmerian Bosporus, had been annexed by the

great Mithridates and retained by his son Pharnaces, after whose death it became dependent on Rome.
